The two weakest reactions (rxn_012 and rxn_014) compound to reduce confidence below threshold. Conceptually sound as a metabolically-congruent alternative, but the experimental evidence for specific substrates is insufficient.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine (DL-2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid)\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network addresses the central bottleneck in prebiotic valine synthesis: the upstream generation of branched C4 aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde) from simple feedstocks. Three independent upstream routes produce isobutyraldehyde \u2014 Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on magnetite, NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification of acetaldehyde, and spark discharge radical chemistry \u2014 which then feed into three terminal pathways to valine: Strecker synthesis, Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route, and reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate. The network explicitly models the ~20-fold yield deficit of valine relative to glycine as an inherent consequence of branching disfavored in abiotic aldol chemistry (Keefe, Newton, Miller 1995). Environmental transitions proceed from hydrothermal CO2 fixation and FTT synthesis, through surface Strecker/condensation chemistry, to biochemical hydrolysis and assembly. Four hub molecules (CO, HCN, acetaldehyde, isobutyraldehyde) create network density and redundancy.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"Hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"start